[2026-07-13T17:35:42.025Z] [INFO]         "content": "===planner.rs===\n921 src/agentic_coding/planner.rs\n11://! messages exchanged and the tool names the agentic CLI advertised, it decides\n15://! Stored recipe: `web_search → web_fetch → write_file(formalize) → run_command(verify) → final`.\n16://! The general fallback is likewise bounded, advertised, and deterministic.\n24:use super::file_read::{file_read_task_for, plan_file_read_step};\n50:/// The path the planner writes the knowledge base to.\n71:/// The tool capabilities the planner's recipe relies on.\n74:/// the planner (to pick which advertised tool to call for each recipe step) and\n76:/// tool of this kind) classify tool names through [`tool_capability`] — so the\n79:pub enum Capability {\n82:    Read,\n83:    Write,\n87:impl Capability {\n88:    /// The associative-package capability key that grants an agentic client the\n89:    /// right to drive a tool of this kind, e.g. `tool:capability:write`. Grants\n90:    /// are by *capability class*, not by tool name, so any CLI's naming\n91:    /// (`write`, `write_file`, `edit`, `patch`, …) maps to the same permission.\n95:            Self::Search => \"tool:capability:search\",\n96:            Self::Fetch => \"tool:capability:fetch\",\n97:            Self::Read => \"tool:capability:read\",\n98:            Self::Write => \"tool:capability:write\",\n99:            Self::Run => \"tool:capability:run\",\n104:/// Classify an advertised tool name into the [`Capability`] it provides.\n110:pub fn tool_capability(name: &str) -> Option<Capability> {\n114:/// Plan the next agentic step from the conversation and advertised tools.\n120:    // (it requires both an AST/CST intent word *and* a self-reference). A self-AST\n205:    if let Some(file_task) = file_read_task_for(&task) {\n206:        return Some(plan_file_read_step(&file_task, messages, tool_names));\n230:    let writes = progress.count(Capability::Write);\n231:    if let Some(tool) = tool_for(tool_names, Capability::Write) {\n232:        if writes == 0 {\n233:            return plan_one(tool, write_arguments(PLAN_PATH, &plan.links_notation()));\n235:        if writes == 1 {\n236:            return plan_one(tool, write_arguments(&plan.target, &plan.content));\n240:        tool_for(tool_names, Capability::Run).filter(|_| !progress.done(Capability::Run))\n259:/// OpenAI-compatible `tool_calls` turn.\n262:    if progress.done(Capability::Run) {\n269:    if let Some(tool) = tool_for(tool_names, Capability::Run) {\n274:        \"I can run `{command}` when the client advertises a shell tool such as `bash`, `shell`, or `run_command`.\"\n283:/// write a generated document to `path`, verify it by running `verify_command`,\n293:    /// The sandbox-allowlisted command that reads the document back for verification.\n295:    /// The inline final answer returned once the write and verify steps are done.\n299:/// Plan the next step of a [`DocumentRecipe`]: `write → verify → final`. Steps whose\n300:/// capability the CLI did not advertise (or the conversation already satisfied) are\n309:    // Step 1: write the generated document.\n311:        tool_for(tool_names, Capability::Write).filter(|_| !progress.done(Capability::Write))\n313:        return plan_one(tool, write_arguments(recipe.path, &recipe.document));\n315:    // Step 2: verify by reading the document back.\n317:        tool_for(tool_names, Capability::Run).filter(|_| !progress.done(Capability::Run))\n330:    let search_tool = tool_for(tool_names, Capability::Search);\n331:    let fetch_tool = tool_for(tool_names, Capability::Fetch);\n332:    let write_tool = tool_for(tool_names, Capability::Write);\n333:    let run_tool = tool_for(tool_names, Capability::Run);\n339:        if !progress.done(Capability::Search) {\n345:        if !progress.done(Capability::Fetch) {\n358:    // Step 3: write the formalized knowledge base.\n359:    if let Some(tool) = write_tool {\n360:        if !progress.done(Capability::Write) {\n361:            return plan_one(tool, write_arguments(KB_PATH, &formalized.links_notation));\n364:    // Step 4: verify by reading the file back.\n366:        if !progress.done(Capability::Run) {\n376:/// The issue-#538 recipe: search → fetch (Wikidata lexemes) → write the enriched\n382:/// not advertise are skipped.\n391:    let search_tool = tool_for(tool_names, Capability::Search);\n392:    let fetch_tool = tool_for(tool_names, Capability::Fetch);\n393:    let write_tool = tool_for(tool_names, Capability::Write);\n394:    let run_tool = tool_for(tool_names, Capability::Run);\n400:        if !progress.done(Capability::Search) {\n406:        if !progress.done(Capability::Fetch) {\n415:    // Step 3: write the enriched meaning block.\n416:    if let Some(tool) = write_tool {\n417:        if !progress.done(Capability::Write) {\n418:            return plan_one(tool, write_arguments(concept.kb_path, &block));\n421:    // Step 4: verify by reading the enriched block back (mirrors the formalization\n422:    // recipe; `cat` is the allowlisted read the sandbox workspace supports).\n424:        if !progress.done(Capability::Run) {\n434:/// The issue-#538 diagram recipe: write the generated mermaid document → verify →\n437:/// so the loop *documents itself*. Steps whose tool the CLI did not advertise are\n454:/// The issue-#538 self-AST recipe: write the generated CST/AST-in-data document →\n458:/// whose tool the CLI did not advertise are skipped.\n474:/// The issue-#558 self-healing recipe: write the generated repair-case document →",
